<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-101-368  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 101 368.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Dec 11 1989 v3 n50 p24(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Lawyers opt for changes to protest procedures. (the Bid ProtestCommittee of the American Bar Association's Section on PublicContract Law) (Comment) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doyle, Gerard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A report from the Bid Protest Committee of the American BarAssociation's Section on Public Contract Law recommends changes inthe protest procedures, recommending improvements in currentforums rather than suggesting changes in any forum's jurisdiction.andO;The report is titled 'The Protest Experience Under the Competitionin Contracting Act'; it focuses on the General Accounting Office(GAO) and the General Services Administration Board of ContractAppeals (GSBCA).andP;  Among the recommended changes are improvementsto the agency-level protest process and the Federal AcquisitionRegulation to make them more believable; reconsideration of theGAO's standard for granting fact-finding conferences; inclusion ofa determination of whether agencies violated statutes orregulations in the GAO's standard of review; and specificationbeforehand of who will be attending informal conferences.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ReportsGovernment ContractsGovernment RegulationCompetitive BiddingGovernment AgencyContractorsA.B.A.andO;United States. General Accounting OfficeUnited States. General Services Administration. Board of ContractAppeals.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>